{"key":"post-12476485","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12476485</id>\n<content>A couple of points need to be considered here.&amp;nbsp; If you stack them after first flush, you protect the contaminant spores that have landed on the surfaces that are then sandwiched, allowing them to germinate more easily.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In addition, the substrates will dry out much sooner, because you have six sides exposed to air instead of one side.&amp;nbsp; If you try to crank up the humidifier to make up for this, you lose a major pinning trigger.&amp;nbsp; A humidifier is only supposed to provide humidity.&amp;nbsp; It's not intended to replace substrate moisture or keep it steady.&amp;nbsp; Using a humidifier in this way will negatively effect pinning.&amp;nbsp; You shouldn't have visible moisture on the surface of a substrate from a humidifier.&amp;nbsp; That's the job of misting, and then the substrate needs to dry somewhat before the next misting session.&amp;nbsp; It's the ebb and flow of moisture content that is one of the big pinning triggers.&amp;nbsp; I wouldn't stack large substrates, especially after a flush.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I'd also put the humidifier on the bottom, not the top.&amp;nbsp; Humidity tends to stratify towards the top of a mini-greenhouse anyway, so putting the humidifier on the bottom mixes the air up more.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12476754</next>\n<prev>12476403</prev>\n<first>12476075</first>\n<last>12484320</last>\n<when>1272556810</when>\n<utime>04/29/10 07:00 PM</utime>\n</post>"}